data.name: [TIE-902] Update Outlook Organization Charts
data.notes:
Summary

This task involves updating Microsoft 365/Outlook organizational charts to accurately display current company reporting relationships and hierarchy. The goal is to automate organizational visibility through proper Microsoft 365 configuration, eliminating the need for HR to maintain separate organizational documentation. This will improve organizational transparency and reduce administrative overhead across the company.

Value or Impact

Operational Value: Eliminates manual HR workload for maintaining separate org charts, reducing administrative burden and potential for outdated information.
Productivity Impact: Enables 50-500 employees to quickly identify reporting relationships and contact appropriate team members without consulting external documentation.
User Experience: Provides always-current organizational visibility through familiar Outlook interface, improving internal communication efficiency.

Acceptance Criteria

    All manager-employee relationships correctly displayed in Outlook/Microsoft 365
    Organization charts automatically reflect current company structure without manual intervention
    HR workload reduced by eliminating need for separate org chart maintenance
    Employees can easily navigate reporting structures through Outlook
    All user profiles updated with accurate job titles, departments, and reporting managers
    Phone numbers populated in signatures to prevent blank fields

Technical Details

Platform: Microsoft 365/Outlook, Azure Active Directory
Implementation Method: PowerShell scripting with Microsoft Graph module
Data Source: HR-provided employee directory (CSV format with names, titles, departments, managers)
Known Issues: 

    Approximately 18 accounts with onmicrosoft.com domains cannot be updated due to local AD sync issues
    Directory sync currently broken between local AD and Azure AD
    Some users have duplicate profiles that need consolidation

Affected Systems / Integrations

    Microsoft 365/Outlook
    Azure Active Directory (Entra ID)
    Local Active Directory (sync needs restoration)
    Email signature templates
    Microsoft Graph API
    PowerShell automation scripts

Next Steps or Analyst Notes

Current Progress:    PowerShell script created and tested, successfully updated 77/96 accounts
    Remaining blockers primarily related to onmicrosoft.com accounts requiring AD sync restoration
    Related task [TIE-2230] - Microsoft People Details Updates contains more recent progress

Immediate Actions Needed:

    Restore Microsoft local AD sync to cloud to unblock onmicrosoft.com account updates
    Complete phone number population for all managers to prevent blank signature fields
    Consider splitting into formal project due to expanding scope and complexity
    Evaluate granting HR (Jennifer Fedewa) limited admin permissions for ongoing maintenance

Known Issues to Resolve:

    Will Ness, Sarah Hildestad, Donald Pelletier need manager relationships fixed (onmicrosoft accounts)
    Multiple duplicate profiles need consolidation
    Justin Bilodeau's account requires email migration from onmicrosoft to standard domain

----------------------------------------

Original Description (Retained)

Description of Change:
Update Microsoft Outlook organization charts to accurately reflect current company reporting structure and hierarchy.

User Story:
As an employee, I want to see accurate organizational charts in Outlook so that I can understand reporting relationships and contact the right people without relying on separate, manually-maintained org charts.

Success Criteria:

    All manager-employee relationships are correctly displayed in Outlook
    Organization charts automatically reflect current company structure
    HR workload is reduced by eliminating need for separate org chart maintenance
    Employees can easily navigate reporting structures through Outlook

Business Justification:
Currently, organization charts in Outlook are inaccurate, requiring HR to maintain separate organizational documentation. Automating this through proper Microsoft 365 configuration will improve organizational visibility and reduce administrative overhead.

data.name: [TIE-866] Update bot logic for Safety Meetings
data.notes:
Name:
Leslie Onley

Email address:
leslie.onley@safetyservicescompany.com

Which Department are you representing?:
Customer Service

What kind of Impact is this having?:
Full Stoppage (Revenue Impacting)

What type of request is this?:
Software Issue or Bug

Software Name & Version:
Penguin 

Steps to Reproduce:
Open Penguin use CID 242967

Navigate to the Meetings tab 

Observe that two invoices are listed:

One for an active subscription (Safety Meetings).

One for a Print Fee, which shows as an expired subscription due to missing contract dates.

Issue: The bot responsible for sending out Safety Meetings is currently not dispatching them to clients who have a Print Fee invoice listed on the same tab. Since Print Fee invoices do not have contract dates, the system flags them as an "expired subscription." The bot appears to interpret this as the overall subscription being expired and skips sending the Safety Meetings entirely.

Request: Can we update the bot’s logic to ignore Print Fee invoices when determining if a subscription is active? Since the Print Fee is not tied to an active subscription (and doesn't affect meeting eligibility), the bot should still send Safety Meetings if a valid Safety Meetings subscription is present.

Expected vs Actual Behavior:
Expected Behavior:
The bot should send out Safety Meetings to clients who have an active Safety Meetings subscription, regardless of whether a Print Fee invoice is present on the Meetings tab.

Actual Behavior:
The bot does not send Safety Meetings if a Print Fee invoice is also listed on the Meetings tab. Since the Print Fee lacks contract dates, it is marked as an "expired subscription," which causes the bot to incorrectly treat the entire subscription as expired. 

What should we call this?:
Safety Meetings and Print fees on Penguin

NA
